'''Advanced Digital Broadcast''' ('''ADB''') is a company which provides and integrates software, system and service [[solution]]s to [[Pay television|pay-TV]] operators, content producers and property owners.

ADB's global headquarters is located in [[Eysins]], [[Switzerland]]; they have research and development facilities in [[Poland]] and in [[Italy]] and an Operations division in [[Taipei]], [[Taiwan]]. ADB has a local offices in several countries in [[Europe]], the [[United States]] and [[Asia]].

Founded in 1995, ADB initially focused on developing and marketing software for [[digital TV]] [[processors]] and expanded its business to the design and manufacture of digital TV equipment in 1997. The company sold its first [[set-top box]] in 1997 and since then has been delivering a number of set-top boxes, and [[Residential gateway|Gateway]] devices, together with advanced software platforms.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://media.corporate-ir.net/media_files/IROL/19/193256/Annual_Report_2010.pdf|title=ADB Group Annual Report 2010}}</ref> ADB has sold over 60 million devices worldwide to cable, satellite, IPTV and broadband operators. ADB employs over 500 people, of which 70% are in engineering functions.<ref name="satkurier">[http://www.satkurier.eu/news/46055/adb-celebrates-15-milllion-iptv-decoders.html SAT Kurier, March 2009]</ref>

==History==

In 1995, ADB was founded by Andrew Rybicki with an initial focus on developing and marketing software for advanced digital TV processors.{{cn|date= June 2018}}

In 1997, ADB started designing and manufacturing of digital TV equipment. ADB designed its first commercial set-to box, and established its dedicated R&D facility in Poland and corporate headquarters in Taiwan.{{cn|date= June 2018}}

Between 1998 and 2000 offices were opened in Australia, and Spain, and ADB sold its one millionth set-top box.{{cn|date= June 2018}}

In 2001, ADB announced the development of an open standard set-top box middleware solution based on the [[Multimedia Home Platform]] (MHP) specification and established its worldwide headquarters in Geneva, Switzerland. The company sold its two millionth set-top box.{{cn|date= June 2018}}

In 2002, the company opened its Americas headquarters in Chicago (since moved to Denver).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allbusiness.com/technology/telecommunications-conferencing/292768-1.html |title=All Business, October 8, 2002, Poland runs first MHP tests in conjunction with ADB |publisher=Allbusiness.com |date=8 October 2002 |accessdate=13 January 2012}}{{dl|date= July 2018}}</ref>{{dl|date= July 2018}} and became the world's first set-top box provider to launch an MHP digital receiver, the i-CAN 3000, in Finland.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitv.fi/sivu.asp?path=9;1239;3392;3228 |title=DigiTV, June 2002 |publisher=Digitv.fi |accessdate=13 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927062637/http://www.digitv.fi/sivu.asp?path=9;1239;3392;3228 |archive-date=27 September 2011 |dead-url=yes |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

In 2005, ADB Group was floated on the Swiss Stock Exchange (SWX)
<ref name="adb history">{{cite web|url=http://www.adbglobal.com/?q=node/115 |title=ADB website – History |publisher=Adbglobal.com |accessdate=13 January 2012}}</ref> and ADB secured its first major IPTV contract to supply set-top boxes to [[Telefónica]]  in Spain.<ref name="Digital TV Group, June 2005">{{cite web |author=Lovelacemedia |url=http://www.dtg.org.uk/news/news.php?id=952 |title=Digital TV Group, June 2005 |publisher=Dtg.org.uk |date=20 June 2005 |accessdate=13 January 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314063447/http://www.dtg.org.uk/news/news.php?id=952# |archive-date=14 March 2012 |dead-url=yes |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The company unveiled its first single-chip [[H.264/MPEG-4 AVC|MPEG-4 AVC]] based set-top box, the ADB-7800TW.

In 2015, ADB rebranded and changed the company logo.<ref>https://www.adbglobal.com/adbs-newly-launched-connected-solutions-win-ibc-best-of-show-award/</ref>

