'''Business reporting''' or '''enterprise reporting''' refers to both "the public reporting of operating and financial data by a business enterprise,"<ref>{{cite web|last=Lymer|first=Andrew|title=BUSINESS REPORTING ON THE INTERNET|url=http://www.cs.trinity.edu/rjensen/Calgary/CD/iasb/busrepw.pdf|accessdate=Nov 6, 2013}}</ref> and "the regular provision of information to decision-makers within an organization to support them in their work."<ref>{{cite web|last=Hill|first=Gregory|title=a guide to enterprise reporting|url=http://ghill.customer.netspace.net.au/reporting/definition.html|accessdate=Nov 6, 2013}}</ref> It is a fundamental part of the larger movement towards improved [[business intelligence]] and [[knowledge management]].{{According to whom|date=October 2018}} Implementation often involves [[Extract, transform, load|extract, transform, and load]] (ETL) procedures in coordination with a [[data warehouse]] and then using one or more [[List of reporting software|reporting tools]].{{cn|date=October 2018}} Reports can be distributed in print form, via [[email]] or accessed via a corporate [[intranet]].{{cn|date=October 2018}}

With the expansion of [[information technology]] there has been an increase in the production of unified reports which join different views of an organization in one place.<ref>Moeller, Robert (2007). COSO Enterprise Risk Management: Understanding the New Integrated ERM Framework. Wiley. {{ISBN|0-471-74115-9}}.</ref> This reporting process involves querying data sources with different [[logical data model|logical model]]s to produce a [[human readable]] report. For example, a decision maker may need to query a [[human resources]] databases and a [[Capital improvement plan|capital improvements]] databases to show how efficiently space is being used across an entire corporation.

Reporting can also be used for verification and cross-checks. Audit teams like FINRA and SEC adhere to reports for all business firms. [[Standard Business Reporting]] is a group of international programs instigated by a number of governments with the end of make business the centre when it comes to managing business-to-government reporting obligations.<ref>{{Cite web
 |title       = Standard Business Reporting Program
 |url         = http://www.sbr.gov.au
 |publisher   = Commonwealth of Australia
 |year        = 2002
 |accessdate  = 14 October 2010
 |quote       = Reducing the reporting burden for business.
}}</ref>

